  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Supporting the reach of global coverage in LLITNs for sustainable prevention of Malaria in Burundi</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Malaria is endemic and a leading cause of morbidity and mortality in Burundi.  It accounts for 40% of medical consultations and is the leading cause of deaths in hospitals (36%).  The entire population is at risk of malaria, and pregnant women and children under the age of 5 are particularly vulnerable.  In line with the priorities of the Malaria National Strategic Plan (NSP) (2013-2017), this grant finances the logistics and distribution of long-lasting insecticidal nets (LLINs) during the 2017 mass campaign;  training for case management activities; integrated community case management in 12 districts;  mass media and community sensitization on malaria prevention and treatment.  The National Malaria Program&#x2019;s main goals by end 2017 include reducing both malaria morbidity, and malaria infection particularly in children.  It will also ensure that &#x2265;90% of the population slept under an insecticide treated net the previous night, promote access to Intermittent Preventive Treatment during pregnancy among all eligible women attending antenatal care and confirm 100% of suspected malaria cases and ensure access to antimalarial treatment according to national guidelines.  These interventions will be implemented by Caritas, as well as the &#x201C;Programme National Int&#xE9;gr&#xE9; de Lutte contre le Paludisme&#x201D; (PNILP), in order to ensure that the objectives of the NSP are met.</narrative>
  </description>
